name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: @corvuseditions On my reading Guillaume is objecting to the word abstentionism because it gives the false impression of indifference to what the state does and to the struggle against the state. Therefore he prefers distinguishing between different kinds of political struggle one can engage in.
name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: @corvuseditions I don't understand your point. Abstention from parliamentary politics is def a core anarchist position from 1872 onwards. So I'm confused about the claim that "abstentionism remained one anarchist position". This implies other distinct anarchist positions on the topic.
name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: What makes me especially annoyed is that Marx and Engels misrepresent anarchism in this manner after they had already been told by anarchists that they were wrong. The anarchist James Guillaume said the following to their faces at the 1872 Hague Congress of the 1st International:  https://t.co/j1jRfxngSO
name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: Why do Marxist historians think anarchists weren't in favour of political struggle? Because Marx and Engels claim anarchists are against political struggle in a number of letters. The Marxist historians read these and just repeat their misrepresentations as fact.
name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: This is a point anarchist authors make over and over again. For example, Malatesta's anarchist programme, which was adopted by the Italian anarchist union, held that: "from the economic struggle one must pass to the political struggle, that is to the struggle against government".
name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: Anarchism was in favour of class struggle and was only against political struggle in the sense of parliamentary politics. It was in favour of political struggle outside of and against the state eg workers engaging in direct action in order to end laws against abortion.
name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: I'm continuously mad about Marxist historians of socialism just making things up. Today I read Georges Haupt claim that Marxism was in favour of class struggle + political struggle, whilst anarchism was opposed to political struggle. This is false.
name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: Quoted in Georges Haupt, Aspects of International Socialism 1871-1914 (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1986), p18.
name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: In 1893 Engels is reported to have said that he "would prefer the Russians - and everybody else too - to stop fishing around for quotations from Marx and Engels and begin thinking instead in the way that Marx would have thought in their position."
name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: Over a century prior to Taylor Swift's world changing break from the fearless era into the speak now era, the German philosopher Karl Marx ended his young Hegelian radical republican era during the mid 1840s and begun his materialist communist era.
name: Zoe Baker

label: far-left
tweet: By controlling the conditions of engagement, by choosing time and place, blending in the local population, and maximizing surprise, stealth, and secrecy, the "small war" fighter can achieve a lot by not fighting directly.  Deception and subterfuge are the guerillas allies.
name: Autonomy & Anarchy

label: far-left
tweet: How large are they? Can they move easily? Do you have the advantage of mobility? Heavy weighted down troops have a hard time with lighter infantry. Can you outrange them, do hit & runs, surprise ambushes, skirmish? Can you be like a vapor, & never give them a target to strike at?
name: Autonomy & Anarchy

label: far-left
tweet: How is their morale? Their attitude? Their demeanor? Their discipline? How angry are they, & can that be used against them? Will they ignore calmer heads & charge into certain doom, if given the right incentive? Do they care about something, and will they rush to defend it?
name: Autonomy & Anarchy

label: far-left
tweet: Wage another type of war.  What else could hurt your opponent?  Is there a way to hamper their transportation? Every army needs the ability to move, is there a way to make that impossible? And vehicles are expensive. How costly can you make their every move or gathering?
name: Autonomy & Anarchy

label: far-left
tweet: Guerilla means "Small war."  It's the art of fighting someone who is stronger then you. Numerically, in firepower, whatever.  It's at least as old as Sun Tzu and Fabius, if not as old as warfare itself.  They both realized, if you can't face an enemy directly, then don't.
name: Autonomy & Anarchy

label: far-left
tweet: @velardass And, the best thing afterwards, is to learn from wherever.  Getting together with folx from other disciplines, seeing what works from that, augmenting your own approach, it's all so fun, and makes you just... Better.  There's always something more to learn.
